-----------------------------------------------------------------------
|  CHAPTER 7 - NAVIGATION: USING ANCHOR TAGS                          |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

- The <a> Tag

    - The <a> Tag is used to link to other HTML documents.

        <a href="http://www.Apress.com">Click here to open the Apress website</a>


    - List of Anchor Tag Attributes

        Global Parameter      Global Parameter Purpose
        -----------------------------------------------------------------------
        download              Specify if an element content is editable or not

        media                 Specify context menu for the HTML5 element (tag)

        href                  Specify custom data attributes for your document

        hreflang              Specifies if an element is draggable (or is not)

        rel                   Specifies a drop processing (copy, move or link)

        target                Specify visibility (relevancy) for each element

        type                  Specify spelling and grammar check for elements

        charset               Specifies to execute scripts after HTML Parsing

        coords                Specify a keystroke shortcut to focus an element

        name                  Allows in-line CSS style declaration for element

        rev                   Specifies the tabbing order for that element

        shape                 Specifies extra information regarding an element



- Anchor Tag Attributes

    - The HREF Attribute

        The href (or 'hypertext reference') attribute is used to specify a URL for the link.

        <a href="http://www.Apress.com">Click here to open the Apress website</a>


    - The HREFLANG Attribute

        This attribute allows you to specify the language used by your hypertext link.
          The language codes are defined in ISO 639.

        <a href="http://www.Apress.com" hreflang="fr">Bonjour! www.Apress.com</a>


    - The DOWNLOAD Attribute

        This attribute tells the HTML5 parser that the file should be downloaded, rather than
          loaded and parsed.

        <a href="!http://WallaceJackson.com/MT240.gif" download>Download Logo!</a>


    - The MEDIA Attribute

        The global 'media' attribute can be used with the anchor tag.

        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" media="screen">iTV Set - Display: Screen</a>


    - The TARGET Attribute

        This attribute allows you to specify the location your application opens your URL in.
          The options are '_blank', '_self', '_parent', and '_top'.

        <!-- Open link in current tab, this is the default -->
        <a href=http://iTVset.com" target="_self">Replace this site with iTV Set</a>

        <!-- Open link in new tab -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" target="_blank">Open iTV Set in a new Tab</a>

        <!-- Used for frames, rarely used these days -->
        <a href=http://iTVset.com" target="_parent">Open iTV Set in Parent Frame</a>
        <a href=http://iTVset.com" target="_top">Open iTV Set in the Full Window</a>
        <a href=http://iTVset.com" target="framename">Open iTV Set in this Frame</a>


    - The REL Attribute

        This attribute allows you to define the relationship that exists between the current
          document and the link.  Here are the possible values for the 'rel' attribute:

          REL Parameter          REL Parameter Purpose
          ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
          alternate              Specifies an alternate version of HTML5 document

          author                 Specifies your author profile for HTML5 document

          bookmark               Specifies permanent URL to bookmark the document

          help                   Specifies the URL (a link) to the help document

          license                Specifies a URL (a link) to a copyright document

          next                   Specifies next document in a series of documents

          nofollow               Specify spelling and grammar check for elements

          noreferrer             Specifies to execute scripts after HTML parsing

          prefetch               Specify a keystroke shortcut to focus an element

          prev                   Allows in-line CSS style declaration for element

          search                 Specifies the tabbing order for that element

          tag                    Specifies extra information regarding an element


        <!-- Create an alternate version of a linked document -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="alternate">Alternate iTV Version</a>

        <!-- Reference an author profile -->
        <a href=http://www.WallaceJackson.com" rel="author">Author Website</a>

        <!-- Create a bookmark link for a linked document -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="bookmark">Bookmark for iTV Set Site</a>

        <!-- Create a help document for a linked document -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="help">iTV Set Website Help Document</a>

        <!-- Create a license document for a linked document -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="license">Copyright License Document</a>

        <!-- Designate the next document in a series -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="next">The Next Document in a Series</a>

        <!-- Specify to search engines that a link should not be followed -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="nofollow">Do Not Follow (Rank) Link</a>

        <!-- Hide the fact that links to another site came from your website -->
        <a href=http://iTVset.com" rel="noreferrer">No Site Referrer Info Sent</a>

        <!-- Preload a document before it is needed -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="prefetch">Prefetch This Document</a>

        <!-- Designate the previous document in a series -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="prev">Previous Document in a Series</a>

        <!-- Create a search tool for a document -->
        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rel="search">Custom Search Utility Link</a>

        <!-- Instruct search engines robots that link text is a relevant keyword -->
        <a href=http://iTVset.com/itv-ebooks" rel="tag">Tag the ebooks keyword</a>


    - The TYPE Attribute

        Anchor tags support the definition of a MIME type using the 'type' attribute.

        <a href=http://iTVset.com" type="text/html">iTV Set: An HTML Website!</a>



- Anchor Tag Legacy Attributes Not Supported in HTML5

    - The CHARSET Attribute

        This attribute specifies the character set used.

        <a href=http://iTVset.com" charset="UTF-8">iTV Set: A UTF-8 Website!</a>


    - The COORDS Attribute

        This attribute creates coordinates for an image map.

        <a href=http://iTVset.com" shape="rect" coords="0,0,240,320">Image Map</a>


    - The NAME Attribute

        This attribute allows a name to be created for a link.  The 'id' attribute should be
          used instead.

        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" name="anchorname">iTV Set Anchor Name</a>


    - The REV Attribute

        This attribute was used to create reverse relationships.  It is the opposite of the
          'rel' attribute.

        <a href=http://www.iTVset.com" rev="alternate">An Opposite of an iTV Set</a>


    - The SHAPE Attribute

        This attribute tells the parsing engine the shape (rect or circle) used for the file
          referenced using an 'href' parameter.  It is used in conjunction with 'coords' to
          create image maps.

        <a href=http://iTVset.com" shape="circle" coords="0,0,240,320">Image Map</a>